	id="Exa_SequenceConvergeInfty">
	<texsupport href="../Analysis_TeXSupport.xml"/>
	
	<title>Sequences Converging to Infinity: Examples</title>
	<showme>
		<statement>
			<para>Show that the sequence <latex magnify="yes">(x_n)</latex> with <latex magnify="yes">x_n = n</latex> converges to <latex>+\infty</latex>.</para>
		</statement>
		<answer type="Solution">
			<para>Let <latex>u\in \RNr</latex> be given. We need to find some <latex><![CDATA[ n_0 > 0 ]]></latex> such that</para>
			<math.display>
				<latex><![CDATA[ x_n \geq u ]]></latex>
			</math.display>
			<para>for all <latex>n\geq n_0</latex>. To establish the existence of such <latex>n_0</latex> recall that 
				<subordinate>
					<hot><latex>\NNr</latex> is not bounded above</hot>
					<crossref>
						<theorem.ref theoremID="Thm_NNotBoundedAbove"/>
						<para>Look up this fact.</para>
					</crossref>
				</subordinate>. Therefore there exists <latex>n_0\in \NNr</latex> with <latex><![CDATA[ n_0 \geq u ]]></latex>. Now, if <latex>n\geq n_0</latex>, we find</para>
			<math.display>
				<latex><![CDATA[ x_n = n \geq n_0 \geq u ]]></latex>
			</math.display>
			<para>This means that</para>
			<math.display>
				<latex>\lim_{n\to\infty} n \ =\ +\infty .</latex>
			</math.display>
		</answer>
	</showme>
</showme.pack>